    <!-- TIMELINE -->
    <section id="timeline" class="section section-anchor">
      <h2>Timeline (5:00 PM Dinner)</h2>
      <p>
        This assumes dinner at <span class="highlight">5:00 PM</span>. Prime rib timing for 4.44 kg at 250°F / 120°C is roughly 3–4 hours to 118°F / 47°C plus rests. [page:1]
      </p>

      <h3>Day Before (Dry Brine + Pre-Prep)</h3>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">Anytime (preferably afternoon)</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Season and start dry brine <span class="badge">Prime Rib</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Unwrap roast, pat dry, trim only hard surface fat. Season all over with ~20 g salt and pepper. Place on herb-free rack/tray, uncovered in fridge 24–36 hours. [page:1]
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">Evening</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Make horseradish cream (optional ahead) <span class="badge">Sauce</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Mix sour cream, horseradish, Dijon, lemon juice, salt and pepper. Chill covered in fridge; flavors meld overnight. [web:18]
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Day Of (Serve at 5:00 PM)</h3>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">12:00 PM</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Pull roast from fridge <span class="badge">Prime Rib</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Let roast sit at room temp 2–3 hours to take the chill off. [page:1]
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">1:00 PM</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Prep herb bed & rub <span class="badge">Prime Rib</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Layer rosemary, thyme, halved garlic bulbs, bay leaves, and lemon peel in roasting pan, drizzle with olive oil. Make garlic–rosemary–mustard–oil rub and set aside. [page:1]
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">1:15 PM</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Preheat oven & rub roast <span class="badge">Prime Rib</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Preheat oven to 250°F / 120°C. Rub roast with the garlic–herb–mustard oil mix, set directly on herb bed (bones act as rack). Probe the thickest part. [page:1]
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">1:30 PM–4:00 PM</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Low-and-slow roast to 118°F / 47°C <span class="badge">Prime Rib</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Roast at 250°F / 120°C until internal hits 118°F / 47°C (estimate 3–4 hours; check from 3-hour mark). Remove roast and tent loosely. [page:1]
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">While roast rests after low cook (target rest start ~3:45–4:00 PM)</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Turn oven up and start potatoes <span class="badge">Mash</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Crank oven to 500°F / 260°C. Start potatoes around 3:45 PM so they can be mashed and held warm before final sear. [page:1][web:15]
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">3:45 PM</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Boil potatoes <span class="badge">Mash</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Cook potatoes in salted water until very tender, 15–20 minutes; meanwhile warm cream and butter with garlic. [web:15][web:21]
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">4:15 PM</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Mash and finish potatoes <span class="badge">Mash</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Drain, mash/ricer potatoes. Fold in warm garlic cream, butter, sour cream, salt, pepper. Hold covered over very low heat or in a warm oven. [web:15][web:16]
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">4:15–4:30 PM</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Guests arrive; roast resting <span class="badge">Hosting</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Roast has rested 30–60 minutes already. Oven is at 500°F / 260°C, potatoes are done and holding, sauces ready or chilled. [page:1]
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">4:30–4:40 PM</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Final 10–15 min high-heat sear <span class="badge">Prime Rib</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Put roast back into 500°F / 260°C oven for 10–15 minutes until dark, crispy crust develops. [page:1]
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">4:40–4:55 PM</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Rest, make jus, final touches <span class="badge">Finish</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Rest roast 15 minutes while you make pan jus from drippings and adjust seasoning on mash and sauces. [web:1][web:30]
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-time">4:55–5:00 PM</div>
        <div class="timeline-title">Carve and plate <span class="badge">Serve</span></div>
        <div class="note">
          Remove bones in one slab, slice roast into ½–¾ inch slices across the grain. Serve with garlic mash, jus, and horseradish cream. [page:1][web:21]
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- PRIME RIB STEPS -->
    <section id="prime-rib" class="section section-anchor">
      <h2>Prime Rib – Step-by-Step</h2>

      <h3>Day Before – Dry Brine</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Unwrap the 4.44 kg roast, pat very dry, and trim only the hard external fat; keep the soft fat cap. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Season all over with ~20 g salt and black pepper. Go heavy; much falls off and bone weight dilutes saltiness. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Set on a rack or tray, uncovered, in the fridge for 24–36 hours to dry brine. [page:1]</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Day Of – Herb Bed and Rub</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove roast around 12:00 PM to warm for 2–3 hours at room temp. [page:1]</li>
        <li>In a roasting pan, layer rosemary, thyme, halved garlic bulbs, bay leaves, and lemon peel, drizzle with olive oil. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Mix rub: finely chop 2 sprigs worth of rosemary leaves and 3 large garlic cloves; stir with 1 tbsp whole grain mustard and 4 tbsp olive oil. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Preheat oven to 250°F / 120°C. Set roast bone-side down on the herb bed. Rub all surfaces with the garlic–herb–mustard oil. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Insert thermometer into thickest center, avoiding bone. [page:1]</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Low Roast and Reverse Sear</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Roast at 250°F / 120°C until internal temp hits 118°F / 47°C for medium-rare. Expect about 3–4 hours for 4.44 kg; start checking at 3 hours. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Remove roast and tent loosely with foil. Let rest at least 30 minutes and up to 1.5 hours. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Increase oven to 500°F / 260°C while the roast rests. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Just before serving window, return roast to the hot oven for 10–15 minutes to develop a deep brown crust. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Rest another 15–20 minutes before carving to let juices redistribute. [page:1]</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Carving</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Stand roast up and slice along the bones to remove them as a slab. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Turn roast on its side and slice ½–¾ inch slices across the grain. [page:1]</li>
        <li>Serve slices with a little fat cap intact, plus jus and horseradish cream on the side. [web:1][web:18]</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <!-- GARLIC MASH -->
    <section id="garlic-mash" class="section section-anchor">
      <h2>Garlic Mashed Potatoes</h2>

      <h3>Method</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Peel and chunk 4 lb / 1.8 kg Yukon Gold potatoes into even pieces. [web:15][web:21]</li>
        <li>Place in a pot with cold water and a generous pinch of salt; bring to a simmer and cook until very tender, 15–20 minutes. [web:15][web:21]</li>
        <li>In a small pot, gently warm cream, butter, and 6–8 garlic cloves (smashed or minced) until steaming, not boiling. [web:16][web:21]</li>
        <li>Drain potatoes well; let sit 1–2 minutes to steam off excess moisture. [web:15]</li>
        <li>Pass through a ricer or mash until smooth, then fold in warm garlic cream, butter, and sour cream. Season with salt and pepper. [web:15][web:16]</li>
        <li>Optional: Fold in roasted garlic cloves and chives, then hold warm (covered) on very low heat or in a 170–190°F / 75–90°C oven. [web:21][web:17]</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <!-- SAUCES -->
    <section id="sauces" class="section section-anchor">
      <h2>Pan Jus & Horseradish Cream</h2>

      <h3>Pan Jus</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>After removing roast for final rest, pour drippings into a fat separator or bowl; skim excess fat, leaving 2–3 tbsp in pan. [web:1][web:4]</li>
        <li>Place pan over medium heat. Add 1 cup beef stock (and a splash of red wine if using), scraping browned bits. [web:1][web:30]</li>
        <li>Simmer to reduce slightly, taste, adjust salt and pepper, then strain if you prefer a smooth jus. [web:1][web:30]</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Horseradish Cream</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Combine 1 cup sour cream, 3–4 tbsp prepared horseradish, 1 tsp Dijon, and 1–2 tsp lemon juice or vinegar. [web:18]</li>
        <li>Season with salt and pepper; chill at least 30 minutes (or overnight from day before). [web:18]</li>
        <li>Stir before serving; adjust heat with more horseradish if desired. [web:18]</li>
      </ol>
    </section>
  </main>

  <script>
    function updateClock() {
      const el = document.getElementById('clock');
      const now = new Date();
      const time = now.toLocaleTimeString([], { hour: '2-digit', minute: '2-digit' });
      el.textContent = 'Current time: ' + time;
    }
    setInterval(updateClock, 1000);
    updateClock();

    function scrollToSection(id) {
      const el = document.getElementById(id);
      if (el) {
        el.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth' });
      }
    }
  </script>
